\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 which satisfy 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dirunb-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 cannot have any extreme points.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}$
\end_inset

 is a direction of unboundness, then so too is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}/2$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}=\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}/2+\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}/2$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}$
\end_inset

 cannot be an extreme point of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 To rectify this issue, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}=\{\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}\in D\mid\|\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}\|=1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{29}}\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{13}}\widehat{\boldsymbol{d}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are the extreme points of this set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2.d
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
