\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Apply the Representation Theorem and find a representation for the point
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(4,6)^{\top}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x} & =\begin{pmatrix}4\\
6
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =2\begin{pmatrix}2\\
1
\end{pmatrix}+\frac{4}{5}\begin{pmatrix}0\\
5
\end{pmatrix}+\frac{1}{5}\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =2\boldsymbol{d}^{2}+\frac{4}{5}\boldsymbol{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{5}\boldsymbol{x}^{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 is a convex combination of the extreme points plus a direction of unboundness.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

