\begin_layout Section*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the linear program (LP) in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min & \quad\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}\\
\text{s.t.} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined as in question 2 above.
 Apply a method for solving LP in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and find the set of all optimal solutions to this LP for each cost vectors
 below.
 Write each set in an appropriate form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(1,1)^{\top}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}=(2,-1)^{\top}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}=(0,1)^{\top}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that the extreme points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{1}=(4,0)^{\top},\boldsymbol{x}^{2}=(0,5)^{\top}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{3}=(0,0)^{\top}$
\end_inset

, and recall that the extreme directions of unboundedness of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}^{1}=(2,4)^{\top}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}^{2}=(2,1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 We first find the optimal solution for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(1,1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{1}=6\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{2}=3\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore for any direction of unboundedness 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the optimal solution will occur at one of the extreme points
 (or perhaps on an adjacent edge connecting two extreme points).
 A simple calculation shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{1} & =4\\
\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{2} & =5\\
\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{3} & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that the optimal solution for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{3}$
\end_inset

 with optimal value given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{3}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Now we find the optimal solution for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}=(2,-1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{1}=0\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{2}=3\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore for any direction of unboundedness 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the optimal solution will occur at one of the extreme points
 (or perhaps on an adjacent edge connecting two extreme points).
 A simple calculation shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{1} & =8\\
\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{2} & =-5\\
\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{3} & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that the optimal solution for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with optimal value given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{2}=-5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Finally we find the optimal solution for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}=(0,1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{1}=4\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}^{2}=1\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore for any direction of unboundedness 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{d}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the optimal solution will occur at one of the extreme points
 (or perhaps on an adjacent edge connecting two extreme points).
 A simple calculation shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{1} & =0\\
\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{2} & =5\\
\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}^{3} & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that the optimal solutions for the cost vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 occurs on the adjacent edge connecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{3}$
\end_inset

, so they have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}\boldsymbol{x}^{1}+t_{2}\boldsymbol{x}^{3}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},t_{2}\geq0$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}+t_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal value at these optimal points is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}(t_{1}\boldsymbol{x}^{1}+t_{2}\boldsymbol{x}^{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Apply the Simplex Algorithm and find an optimal solution to the linear
 program.
 In every iteration, select the most negative reduced cost.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min & \quad-6x_{1}-14x_{2}-13x_{3}\\
\text{s.t.} & \quad x_{1}+4x_{2}+2x_{3}\leq48\\
 & \quad x_{1}+2x_{2}+4x_{3}\leq60\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We introduce slack variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4},x_{5}\geq0$
\end_inset

 to convert the inequality constraints to equality constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min & \quad-6x_{1}-14x_{2}-13x_{3}\\
\text{s.t.} & \quad x_{1}+4x_{2}+2x_{3}+x_{4}=48\\
 & \quad x_{1}+2x_{2}+4x_{3}+x_{5}=60\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where now 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4},x_{5})^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{pmatrix}2 & 4 & 2 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 2 & 4 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},\quad,\boldsymbol{b}=\begin{pmatrix}48\\
60
\end{pmatrix},\quad\boldsymbol{c}=\begin{pmatrix}-6\\
-14\\
-13\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Then in standard form, our linear program looks like:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad z=\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}\\
\text{s.t.} & \quad A\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b}\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We now perform the simplex algorithm as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
First iteration of the simplex algorithm: 
\series default
We begin by using the slack variables as the initial basis.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}_{B} & =(x_{4},x_{5})^{\top} & \boldsymbol{x}_{N} & =(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})^{\top}\\
\boldsymbol{c}_{B} & =(0,0)^{\top} & \boldsymbol{c}_{N} & =(-6,-14,-13)^{\top}\\
B & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix} & N & =\begin{pmatrix}2 & 4 & 2\\
1 & 2 & 4
\end{pmatrix}\\
B^{-1} & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix} & B^{-1}N & =\begin{pmatrix}2 & 4 & 2\\
1 & 2 & 4
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Our current basic solution and our current objective value are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}} & =B^{-1}\boldsymbol{b} & \widehat{\boldsymbol{z}} & =\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}48\\
60
\end{pmatrix} &  & =(0,0)^{\top}\begin{pmatrix}48\\
60
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(48,60)^{\top} &  & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To determine whether or not this is optimal, we calculate the reduced cost
\series bold
 
\series default
vector:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N}^{\top} & =(\boldsymbol{c}_{N}^{\top}-\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}B^{-1}N)\\
 & =(-6,-14,-13)-(0,0)\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}2 & 4 & 2\\
1 & 2 & 4
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(-6,-14,-13).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N}$
\end_inset

 are negative, so the basis is not optimal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N})_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the more negative component, we select 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 (the second nonbasic variable) as the entering variable.
 To find the leaving variable, we first calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{A}_{2} & =B^{-1}A_{2}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}4\\
2
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}4\\
2
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the second column of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{i,2}$
\end_inset

 denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th entry in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

, we then calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{x}_{2} & =\min_{1\leq i\leq2}\left\{ \frac{\widehat{b}_{i}}{\widehat{a}_{i,2}}\mid\widehat{a}_{i,2}>0\right\} \\
 & =\min\left\{ \frac{48}{4},\frac{60}{2}\right\} \\
 & =12.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the leaving variable is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}$
\end_inset

 (the first basic variable) corresponding to the minimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widehat{b}_{i}/\widehat{a}_{i,2}\mid\widehat{a}_{i,2}>0\}$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the first iteration of the simplex algorithm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Second iteration of the simplex algorithm: 
\series default
We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 in our basis, so let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}_{B} & =(x_{2},x_{5})^{\top} & \boldsymbol{x}_{N} & =(x_{1},x_{4},x_{3})^{\top}\\
\boldsymbol{c}_{B} & =(-14,0)^{\top} & \boldsymbol{c}_{N} & =(-6,0,-13)^{\top}\\
B & =\begin{pmatrix}4 & 0\\
2 & 1
\end{pmatrix} & N & =\begin{pmatrix}2 & 1 & 2\\
1 & 0 & 4
\end{pmatrix}\\
B^{-1} & =\begin{pmatrix}1/4 & 0\\
-1/2 & 1
\end{pmatrix} & B^{-1}N & =\begin{pmatrix}1/2 & 1/4 & 1/2\\
0 & -1/2 & 3
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Our current basic solution and our current objective value are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}} & =B^{-1}\boldsymbol{b} & \widehat{\boldsymbol{z}} & =\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}48\\
60
\end{pmatrix} &  & =(-14,0)^{\top}\begin{pmatrix}12\\
36
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(12,36)^{\top} &  & =-168
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To determine whether or not this is optimal, we calculate the reduced cost
\series bold
 
\series default
vector:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N}^{\top} & =(\boldsymbol{c}_{N}^{\top}-\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}B^{-1}N)\\
 & =(-6,0,-13)-(-14,0)\begin{pmatrix}1/2 & 1/4 & 1/2\\
0 & -1/2 & 3
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(1,7/2,-6).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The third component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N}$
\end_inset

 is negative, so the basis is not optimal.
 Since this is the only negative component, we select 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 (the third nonbasic variable) as the entering variable.
 To find the leaving variable, we first calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{A}_{3} & =B^{-1}A_{3}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1/4 & 0\\
-1/2 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}2\\
4
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1/2\\
3
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

 is the second column of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{i,3}$
\end_inset

 denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th entry in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{A}_{3}$
\end_inset

, we then calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{x}_{3} & =\min_{1\leq i\leq2}\left\{ \frac{\widehat{b}_{i}}{\widehat{a}_{i,3}}\mid\widehat{a}_{i,3}>0\right\} \\
 & =\min\left\{ \frac{12}{1/2},\frac{36}{3}\right\} \\
 & =12.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the leaving variable is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 (the second basic variable).
 This completes the second iteration of the simplex algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Third iteration of the simplex algorithm: 
\series default
We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 in our basis, so let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}_{B} & =(x_{2},x_{3})^{\top} & \boldsymbol{x}_{N} & =(x_{1},x_{4},x_{5})^{\top}\\
\boldsymbol{c}_{B} & =(-14,-13)^{\top} & \boldsymbol{c}_{N} & =(-6,0,0)^{\top}\\
B & =\begin{pmatrix}4 & 2\\
2 & 4
\end{pmatrix} & N & =\begin{pmatrix}2 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\\
B^{-1} & =\begin{pmatrix}1/3 & -1/6\\
-1/6 & 1/3
\end{pmatrix} & B^{-1}N & =\begin{pmatrix}1/2 & 1/3 & -1/6\\
0 & -1/6 & 1/3
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Our current basic solution and our current objective value are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}} & =B^{-1}\boldsymbol{b} & \widehat{\boldsymbol{z}} & =\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}\widehat{\boldsymbol{b}}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1/3 & -1/6\\
-1/6 & 1/3
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}48\\
60
\end{pmatrix} &  & =(-14,-13)^{\top}\begin{pmatrix}6\\
12
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(6,12)^{\top} &  & =-240
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To determine whether or not this is optimal, we calculate the reduced cost
\series bold
 
\series default
vector:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{c}}_{N}^{\top} & =(\boldsymbol{c}_{N}^{\top}-\boldsymbol{c}_{B}^{\top}B^{-1}N)\\
 & =(-6,0,0)-(-14,-13)\begin{pmatrix}1/2 & 1/3 & -1/6\\
0 & -1/6 & 1/3
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(1,5/2,2).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The cost vector consists of strictly positive entries.
 This means that the objective function will 
\emph on
increase 
\emph default
no matter which direction we choose: we have found a local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}=(0,6,12)$
\end_inset

 with objective value given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{z}^{*}=-240$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, this is a global minimum since linear programming problems are
 convex optimization problems.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 5.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 be a feasible solution but not a basic feasible solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $A\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the nonzero entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 According to the book,
\series bold
 
\series default
a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basic solution 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equality constraints of the linear program 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the columns of the constraint matrix corresponding to the nonzero components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So by definition (according to the book), the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the nonzero entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 To complete this problem though, I'll prove the following instead:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\boldsymbol{x}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 nonzero entries where 
\begin_inset Formula $m<k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the columns corresponding to the nonzero entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rank}\,A\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the maximum size of a set of linearly independent columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 as well.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 5.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 be a feasible point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\mid A\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b},\boldsymbol{x}\geq0\}$
\end_inset

 that is not an extreme point.
 Prove that there exists a nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A\boldsymbol{p}=0$
\end_inset

 and,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Hint: use the result from part a).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 is not a basic feasible solution since it is not an extreme point.
 Therefore the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the nonzero entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent and we can find a feasible direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}\neq0$
\end_inset

) satisfying 1 and 2 above.
 For instance, suppose the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 are nonzero and the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 entries are zero where 
\begin_inset Formula $m<k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the set of columns 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{1},\dots,A_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}A_{1}+\cdots+a_{k}A_{k}=0
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 not all zero.
 By scaling the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{i}|<x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(a_{1},\dots,a_{k},0,\dots,0)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 will satisfy 1 and 2 above (it will also be a feasible direction, meaning
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 is feasible).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

